A stakeholder analysis helps you identify which stakeholders are being impacted by a change project, where each stands on receptiveness to the change, and which ones can impact a change project the most. Stakeholder assessment is a critical component of effective business change management because it increases the success of your stakeholder engagement and management.
Read more at airiodion: https://www.airiodion.com/stakeholder-analysis/

UML:TaggedValue.value: Capturing stakeholder goals as part of the design process is extremely important, after all it is the stakeholders who make products successful, not end users. Stakeholder goals can be summarized and captured as Operational Objective elements the system should meet. In general Operational Objectives are performance objectives that can be quantified, measured, and tracked in relation to the deployed system's performance. Since they are system level goals which include both process + product related metrics that are arrived at though scenario analysis. This imply's use cases so the Operational Objective elements are stereotyped use cases. The following template is a best practice in capturing the Operational Objectives: NAME: Provide a brief name as a verb statement OBJECTIVE DESCRIPTION Provide a brief description of the operational objective that the stakeholder has on the system. BACKGROUND Provide any background info that will give the objective context in terms of the stakeholder and their expectations on the system, system performance, and/or process in which the product will be used. EXPECTED OUTCOMES Describe the expected outcome that the system will provide the stakeholder. This should be told from the perspective of the stakeholder. GUARANTEED RESULT Describe the minim outcome the system will provide the stakeholder for this objective. This should be told in the form of a negative sense that the full objective cant or wouldn’t be realized, so what should the stakeholder get in response. INCLUDES List all things that this includes from the stakeholder's perspective. ASSUMPTIONS List any assumptions that this objective is based upon. This could be basic needed functionality, input, operational context, scenario preconditions.

Stakeholder concerns are specifically called out in IEEE 42010, as well as how to address them. The following format is a best practice for documenting stakeholder concerns: CONCERN DESCRIPTION Provide a description of the concern. This should include whay it is important, who it might affect, how it affects any product design decisions. SOURCE FOR CONCERN This is the justification for the concern and who said it. specifically mentioned he stakeholder that was interviewed etc. REFERENCE DATA When creating the concern provide references or links to your data for the concern. This is important to maintain this and traceability because these will be revisited in the architecture phase to ensure that the concerns are met.

This package contains a description of the key stakeholders including what they expect from the system and concerns from their perspective. An example of a good stakeholder description is: STAKEHOLDER'S ROLE Provide a description of the role that the stakeholder plays in the ecosystem where the mission will be executed. BACKGROUND Provide any background information on the stakeholder that helps to solidify their perspective to the development team. RANGE OF INFLUENCE Provide a brief description of their range of influence with regard to the system and the system boundary. STAKEHOLDER"S PERSPECTIVE Provide a brief description of the stakeholders perspective of the system. This should include if the stakeholder thinks the system will enhance their role or if the system is a threat.

UML:TaggedValue.value: Each stakeholder has a role to play and a set of responsibilities that either directly interact with or indirectly influence the system behavior, design, deployment, or operation. It is important to understand stakeholder's responsibilities for the system and within the organization a system will be deployed so that objective and concerns can be prioritized based upon stakeholder impact. As best practice template for describing these elements are as follows: NAME: Provide a brief name as a noun RESPONSIBILITY DESCRIPTION Describe the responsibility the stakeholder has from both the system and the organization perspective. INTERFACE List who the stakeholder will interface with to realize or depend upon for the responsibility.

In most instances some sort of process, tool, set of activities already exists. The pain point elements capture the current pre-product state of the system. Pains can be process related, product related, or lack of product/process that the stakeholder experiences. When capturing pains it is important to understand the context in which the pain is encountered, how often the pain is encountered, and/or what emotional effect that pain has on the user. These pains often are directly correlate to the user experience. The pain points package contains the description of individual pain points identified during the analysis. Specific details as to the nature of the pain point and effects are summarized for each pain point. A pain point is a specific problem that prospective stakeholder (or customers) of your system are experiencing. In other words, pain points are problems told from the prospective of you stakeholders themselves. The following template shows the best practice used for documenting this element when further clarification was need and what each section contains: Pain#- Name PAIN POINT DESCRIPTION Provide a brief description of the pain point and why it is a pain point vs a delta which is something that could be done better. CONTEXT Provide a brief description of the context in which the pain point is encountered or contributes to the overall problem IMPACT Describe the impact of the pain point, such as the entire process breaks down, or the entire solution path is blocked.

The Stakeholder Management Levels Diagram shows the ranking of the stakeholders and where their investment in the project needs to be to show that the project is successful. Knowledge Area: Business Analysis Planning & Monitoring Applicable Task: Conduct Stakeholder Analysis Useful When: Identifying stakeholders involved in your project. Helps the Project Manager and/or Lead Systems Engineer determine which stakeholders will directly interact with a system or process and those outside the organization.

The Stakeholder Onion Diagram is stakeholder analysis tool from the arsenal of project management. It is used to display the relationships of stakeholders to a project which has a set of goals. The Onion Diagram shows how stakeholder activities affect project results and depict how the relationships that subsist in a project environment can influence on a project. A set of libraries and objects provided by this solution make short work of visualizing the stakeholder analysis of a project. Some things to consider when applying this pattern:

The Top Level Stakeholder Interactions Diagram shows the basic interactions that each of the stakeholders provides to the system. This diagram is useful because it provides one view of the interactions at a top level.

The Stakeholder Hierarchy Diagram shows the hierarchy of the stakeholders for the project and the system. The Stakeholder Analysis diagram provides a rational grouping of the stakeholders into similar categories that help to identify areas that could be impacted when the mission is implemented.
